# Skin properties
<a href="mailto:documentation@lithium.com?Subject=Developer Documentation Feedback" target="_top">Send feedback about this document</a>

We recommend that you define skin properties in `skin.properties` when you create a new skin.
It provides an easy way to  quickly define things such as, "all links should be blue," or
"all non-link text should be grey." `skin.properties` is also where you can set
the background color for info messages, set custom fonts and font sizes, and so on.
Studio users can edit skin properties in **Studio > Community Style > Properties**.
Read <a href="https://community.lithium.com/t5/Skins-and-assets/Edit-skin-properties/ta-p/40322" target="_blank">Edit skin properties</a>
for more information.

The table below shows the default skin properties used with non-responsive skins. Skin properties are editable in Studio. The Studio Field column shows the fields in **Studio > Community Style > Properties** that maps to the skin property in the Property column.

Responsive skins use only a limited set of skin properties to specify default cropping sizes for images and assets. For details about skin properties and responsive skins, see the Skin Architecture section of the <a href="https://community.lithium.com/t5/Developer-Documentation/bd-p/dev-doc-portal?section=responsive">Responsive Developer Documentation</a>.


## Skin properties for non-responsive skins

#### Color properties

| Property | Description | Studio Field |
| ---------| ----------- | ------------ |   
| color.foreground | The default text color | Foreground color |
| color.background | The background color for all pages | Background color |
| color.midtone | A tone between foreground and background. Text on both foreground and background should also be readable on midtone. | Midtone color |
| color.rollover | Color for links, such as navigation and breadcrumbs | Rollover color |
| color.selection | A background color to highlight element selection | Selection color |
| color.alert | Color for error/warning messages | Alert color |
| color.safe | Color used for success and confirmation messages | Safe color |
| color.primary_01 | The most prominent accent color used on a page for major dividers, title, and other important page elements| Primary color 1 |
| color.primary_02 | A secondary accent color for less important elements, such as section dividers | Primary color 2 |


